nodes.bodyText:
This looks great but you can move
assertTrue("Admin Button should be displayed", driver().findElements(By.id("admin-panel-btn")).size() > 0); into the accessPageAsAdmin method after the LoginPage line and remove this test.
Same applies to the test below where you can move the assertFalse("Admin Button should not be displayed", driver().findElements(By.id("admin-panel-btn")).size() > 0); into the accessPageFailure method after the LoginPage line and remove the test below as well

"FUBAR - YOU MADE IT" is not going to be the final title so maybe test something that will actually be there. I realize that is the only thing on the page, you could ask the driver for the url:

assertTrue("Logged in as admin, the user can get to the administration panel", driver().getCurrentUrl()
				.contains("/admin"));
2. Instead of finding by id, use a class specific for testing. We try to prefix classes that are used with for testing with t- so in this case you could add the class t-admin-panel-btn or something like that.

XPath really sucks to work with. Again here I would add a specific class for testing beginning with t-.  It is also better to just ask for the title found on the page and then actually do the comparison in the integration test.
Better just to find exactly what you are looking for here.  In this case you could find the title here.

In your integration test page only do comparisons, it should know nothing about the structure of the page - do that on your page object.  For example here you would maybe ask the page object if the admin panel button is present.
Okay sounds good, I will add that instead

Change this Fubar - You Made It text to something like "Admin Panel". You would add it to the messages.properties (translations) file. And here you would have something like
<h1 class="t-admin-panel-title th:text="#{admin.panel.title}">ADMIN PANEL<h1>
The admin.panel.title would be the translation key
You would had the
th:text="#{admin.panel.title}" to the title in the  tags as well
